Why all of the use of static methods?  Statics are globals, as far as the VM
is concerned, and you can run into problems not knowing what code last set
the state.  Unless every client that uses the factory explicitly configures
the factory before using it, you don&#39;t know what you&#39;re getting.

It seems like a cleaner, better OO design to use Factory objects (i.e.,
instances).  Much of what you have written remains the same, but all of the
methods can become instance methods.  Then you &quot;configure&quot; the factory at
construction time.

For example, &quot;production&quot; code can use the default factory constructor.

    myFactory = new Factory()
    thing = myFactory.createThing()

Test code can pass in arguments to the constructor.

    new Factory(false)    OR
    new Factory(overrideThing)    OR
    new Factory().setOverrideThing(overrideThing)

You can even subclass a factory to behave in a different way, which is
something else you can&#39;t do with statics.  As far as how to get a factory to
the class that needs to use it, you can pass it in at construction time, or
set it as an argument, or override the factory creation method in the class
under test

Just some ideas that have worked well for me.

