&gt; In response to my own problems and an earlier question, I&#39;ve been
&gt; thinking about how to test classes that retrieve things from static
&gt; factories.
&gt;
&gt; I don&#39;t want to give up being able to make these factories, but they
&gt; typically are for things that I&#39;d want to use mock objects for
&gt; (persistence, logging, etc).
&gt;
&gt; The requirements I started with were:
&gt;
&gt; 1. The public interface to the factory cannot change.
&gt; 2. The factory&#39;s outputs must be editable at runtime by test classes.
&gt; 3. The factory&#39;s outputs must be editable by classes not in the
&gt; factory&#39;s package.
&gt;
&gt; What I came up with was the regular factory, with some extra logic for
&gt; replacement.  That satisfied #2.  I made the methods protected in order
&gt; to fulfill requirement #1.  Lastly, in order to get around the
&gt; protected restriction for #3, I made a &#39;FactoryAdaptor&#39; that basically
&gt; provided pass-through for those protected methods.
&gt;
&gt; Here&#39;s some quick example code:
&gt;
&gt; public class Factory {
&gt;
&gt;   private static overrideThing=null;
&gt;
&gt;   public static Thing createThing(String thingName) {
&gt;     Thing returnThing;
&gt;     if (overrideThing != null) {
&gt;       returnThing=overrideThing;
&gt;     } else {
&gt;       do what you&#39;d normally do..
&gt;     }
&gt;     return returnThing;
&gt;   }
&gt;
&gt;   protected static void ut_setOverrideThing(Thing overrideThing) {
&gt;     this.overrideThing= overrideThing;
&gt;   }
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; public class FactoryAdaptor extends Factory {
&gt;   public static setOverrideThing(Thing overrideThing) {
&gt;     ut_setOverrideTHing(overrideThing);
&gt;   }
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; In the real implementation, I provided methods to &#39;clear&#39; the override,
&gt; which is more straightforward than setting it to null.  I also provided
&gt; methods for recording the thingNames that were requested.  In the
&gt; future, if I need it, I may change it to specify a list of things to
&gt; return over several requests, but I didn&#39;t need it this time around.
&gt;
&gt; I like this because it doesn&#39;t change the public interface, and the
&gt; test interface can reside in the test source folder.  Those parts of
&gt; the code that exist for unit test functionality are marked that way,
&gt; though I may have gone too far in modifying the method naming
&gt; convention for this.
&gt;
&gt; Usage is pretty straightforward, calls go to the FactoryAdaptor.
&gt;
&gt; Have other folks used this approach, or something similar?  What do you
&gt; all think of this approach to the problem?
&gt;
&gt; Kevin Klinemeier
&gt;
&gt; PS:  It occurs to me now that if the factory were a little different,
&gt; with a single static getCurrent() method and otherwise instance
&gt; methods, this would reduce the nefarious intermingling of the &#39;mocking&#39;
&gt; code, because the current method could return a completely different
&gt; (mock) factory altogether.
